A web-based Human Resources and Payroll Management System built for a university environment. The application supports multiple user roles — Admin, HR, Academic Employees, and Dean/President/Vice-Dean — each with a dedicated portal and tailored set of features.

Tech Stack

Frontend: ASP.NET Web Forms (.aspx) with C# code-behind
Backend: C# / .NET Framework 4.8
Database: Microsoft SQL Server (T-SQL — stored procedures, functions, views)
IDE: Visual Studio (solution file included)


Features
Admin Portal

View all employee profiles and employees per department
Manage official holidays (add/remove)
Manage employee days off
Initiate and update daily attendance records
Fetch yesterday's attendance and employee performance reports
Approve or remove approved leaves
Replace employees and update employment status
Remove deductions for resigned employees

HR Portal

Login and role-based session management
Approve or reject leave requests (annual, accidental, unpaid, compensation, medical)
Add deductions for missing days, missing hours, and unpaid leave
Generate monthly payroll for employees via stored procedure

Academic Employee Portal

Login with department-specific session
Submit leave requests: annual, accidental, unpaid, compensation, medical
View attendance and annual leave account status
View past payroll records
Check personal performance by semester
View and track attendance deductions

Dean / President / Vice-Dean Portal

Dedicated homepages with summary views
Evaluate employees (dean evaluation feature)
Approve or reject annual and unpaid leave requests


Database
The SQL database (Database (M2 sol.).sql) includes:

Full schema creation via stored procedure (createAllTables)
Tables: Employee, Department, Role, Leave, Attendance, Payroll, and more
Computed salary column using a scalar function (HRSalary_calculation) based on base salary, years of experience, and role percentage
Stored procedures for payroll generation (Add_Payroll) and other business logic
Table-valued functions (e.g., MyPerformance) for querying employee performance by period
Sample data insertions in insertions.sql

